</p>
<p>So if you ever need the <code>User</code> object in a service, this is how to get it.</p>
<p>But, it takes a couple of steps: <code>getToken()</code> gives you a pretty unimportant object,
except for the fact that you can call <code>getUser()</code> on it.</p>
<h3 id="the-creepy-anon">The Creepy anon. <a class="headerlink" href="the-user-object#the-creepy-anon" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h3>
<p>But, there's a pitfall: if you are anonymous - so, not logged in - <code>getUser()</code> does
<em>not</em> return <code>null</code>, as you might expect: it returns a string: <code>anon.</code>. I know -
it's super weird. So, if you ever <em>do</em> fetch the user object directly via this service,
check to make sure <code>getUser()</code> returns an object. If it doesn't, the user isn't logged
in.</p>
<h2 id="getting-the-user-in-twig">Getting the User in Twig <a class="headerlink" href="the-user-object#getting-the-user-in-twig" title="Permalink to this headline"><i class="fa fa-link" aria-hidden="true"></i></a></h2>
<p>The <em>one</em> other place where you'll need to fetch the User is inside Twig. In fact,
let's talk about security in general in Twig. Open up <code>base.html.twig</code>.</p>
<p>Earlier, we already showed how to check for a role in Twig: it's via the <code>is_granted()</code>
function:</p>
